PEEQ

εˉp\bar \varepsilon ^pεˉp is the effective/accumulated/equivalent plastic strain(PEEQ). It is used as a scalar measure of the tensor plastic strain εp\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^pεp.
εˉp≡∫0t23εp˙:εp˙ dt=∫0t23∥εp˙∥ dt\bar\varepsilon^p \equiv \int_0^t\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p}:\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p}}\,dt = \int_0^t\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}\|\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p}\|\,dtεˉp≡∫0t​32​εp˙:εp˙​dt=∫0t​32​​∥εp˙∥dt

εˉp˙=23εp˙:εp˙=23∥εp˙∥=γ˙\dot{\bar\varepsilon^p} = \sqrt{\frac{2}{3}\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p}:\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p}} = \sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}\|\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p}\| = \dot\gammaεˉp˙=32​εp˙:εp˙​=32​​∥εp˙∥=γ˙​

In return mapping, we have
εn+1p=εnp+Δγ32sn+1∥sn+1∥\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p_{n+1}=\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^p_n+\Delta \gamma \sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}\frac{\boldsymbol{s}_{n+1}}{\|\boldsymbol{s}_{n+1}\|} \end{aligned}εn+1p​=εnp​+Δγ23​​∥sn+1​∥sn+1​​​

which denotes the relationship between εˉp\bar\varepsilon^pεˉp and εp\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^pεp.

Tensor operator

[Tensor double contraction]
: denotes double contraction of tensors (internal product of second-order tensors).
For 2 second-order tensors A and B:
A:B=tr(A⋅BT)=AijBij (scalar)A:B = \rm{tr}(\it A\cdot \it B^T) = A_{ij}B_{ij}\,(scalar)A:B=tr(A⋅BT)=Aij​Bij​(scalar)

For A with order m and B with order n (m>n), their double contraction is a tensor C with order (m-n):

eg.

  • for A with order 5 and B with order 2:
    Cijk=(A:B)ijk=AijkpqBpqC_{ijk}=(A:B)_{ijk}=A_{ijkpq}B_{pq}Cijk​=(A:B)ijk​=Aijkpq​Bpq​
  • s:s=tr(s⋅sT)\boldsymbol{s}:\boldsymbol{s}=\rm tr(\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{s}^T)s:s=tr(s⋅sT)
    if s\boldsymbol{s}s is symmetric, then s:s=tr(s⋅s)=tr(s2)=∥s∥2\boldsymbol{s}:\boldsymbol{s}=\rm tr(\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{s})=\rm tr(\boldsymbol{s}^2)=\|\boldsymbol{s}\|^2s:s=tr(s⋅s)=tr(s2)=∥s∥2

[Tensor product]
"⊗\otimes⊗" denotes tensor product of tensors.
For tensor A with order m and tensor B with order n, their tensor product is a tensor with order (m+n). Thus each item is:
(A⊗B)i1i2…im+n=Ai1i2⋯im⋅Bim+1⋯im+nA⊗B≠B⊗A\begin{aligned} (A\otimes B)_{i_1 i_2 \dots i_{m+n}} &= A_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_m}\cdot B_{i_{m+1}\cdots i_{m+n}} \\ A \otimes B &\ne B \otimes A \end{aligned}(A⊗B)i1​i2​…im+n​​A⊗B​=Ai1​i2​⋯im​​⋅Bim+1​⋯im+n​​​=B⊗A​

Second-order tensor analysis

Symmetric tensor: T=TT\boldsymbol{T}=\boldsymbol{T}^TT=TT
Skew symmetric tensor: T=−TT\boldsymbol{T}=-\boldsymbol{T}^TT=−TT
Any tensor can be decomposed as
T=sym(T)+skew(T)\boldsymbol{T}=\rm{sym}(\boldsymbol{T})+\rm{skew}(\boldsymbol{T})T=sym(T)+skew(T)

The symmetric part: sym(T)≡12(T+TT)\rm{sym}(\boldsymbol{T})\equiv\frac{1}{2}(\boldsymbol{T}+\boldsymbol{T}^T)sym(T)≡21​(T+TT)
The skew part: skew(T)≡12(T−TT)\rm{skew}(\boldsymbol{T})\equiv\frac{1}{2}(\boldsymbol{T}-\boldsymbol{T}^T)skew(T)≡21​(T−TT)

Split of tensors

The strain tensor can be written as:
ε=εd+εv\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} = \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_d + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_vε=εd​+εv​

volumetric strain tensor:
εv≡13εvIεv=13(I⊗I):ε\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_v&\equiv\frac{1}{3}\varepsilon_v\boldsymbol{I}\\ \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_v&=\frac{1}{3}(\boldsymbol{I}\otimes\boldsymbol{I}):\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \end{aligned}εv​εv​​≡31​εv​I=31​(I⊗I):ε​

volumetric strain:
εv≡I1(ε)=trε=tr∇su=tr∇u\varepsilon_v \equiv I_1(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}) = \rm{tr}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} = \rm{tr}\nabla^{\it s}\boldsymbol{u}=\rm{tr}\nabla\boldsymbol{u}εv​≡I1​(ε)=trε=tr∇su=tr∇u

deviatoric strain tensor:
εd=ε−εvεd=[IS−13I⊗I]:ε=Id:ε\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_d &= \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} - \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_v\\ \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_d &= [\boldsymbol{\rm I}_S-\frac{1}{3}\boldsymbol{I}\otimes\boldsymbol{I}]:\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\mathbf{I}_d : \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \end{aligned}εd​εd​​=ε−εv​=[IS​−31​I⊗I]:ε=Id​:ε​

where trεd=0\rm{tr}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_d=0trεd​=0
The stress tensor can be written as
σ=s+pI\boldsymbol{\sigma}=\boldsymbol{s} + p\boldsymbol{I}σ=s+pI

hydrostatic stress/hydrostatic pressure/mean stress/mean normal pressure:
p≡13trσp \equiv \frac{1}{3}\rm{tr}\boldsymbol{\sigma}p≡31​trσ

deviatoric stress tensor/stress deviator:
s≡σ−pI=Id:σ\boldsymbol{s}\equiv\boldsymbol{\sigma} - p\boldsymbol{I} = \boldsymbol{\rm I}_d:\boldsymbol{\sigma}s≡σ−pI=Id​:σ

Id\boldsymbol{\rm I}_dId​ is a 4th-order tensor named deviatoric projection tensor.
Id≡IS−13I⊗I\boldsymbol{\rm I}_d \equiv \boldsymbol{\rm I}_S - \frac{1}{3}\boldsymbol{I}\otimes\boldsymbol{I}Id​≡IS​−31​I⊗I

IS\boldsymbol{\rm{I}}_SIS​ is a 4th-order tensor named symmetric identity tensor:
Iijkl=12(δikδjl+δilδjk)\boldsymbol{\rm{I}}_{ijkl}=\frac{1}{2}(\delta_{ik}\delta_{jl}+\delta_{il}\delta_{jk})Iijkl​=21​(δik​δjl​+δil​δjk​)

This deviatoric projection tensor can project a second-order symmetric tensor S\boldsymbol{S}S into the deviatoric subspace, i.e. into the space of traceless tensors.
dev(S)≡Id:S\rm {dev}(\boldsymbol{S}) \equiv \boldsymbol{\rm I}_d : \boldsymbol{S}dev(S)≡Id​:S

pIp\boldsymbol{I}pI is called spherical stress tensor:
pI=13(I⊗I):σp\boldsymbol{I}=\frac{1}{3}(\boldsymbol{I}\otimes\boldsymbol{I}):\boldsymbol{\sigma}pI=31​(I⊗I):σ

Thus

ϵijk\epsilon_{ijk}ϵijk​ Condition

Associate flow rule

Associative flow rule assumes plastic strain increment is normal to the yield at that point. Thus we can assume yield function Φ\PhiΦ to be the same as the flow potential function Ψ\PsiΨ.
Φ≡Ψ\Phi \equiv \PsiΦ≡Ψ

In associative models, the evolution equations are given by
ε˙p=γ˙∂Φ∂σ=γ˙N\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}^p=\dot{\gamma}\frac{\partial \Phi}{\partial \boldsymbol{\sigma}}=\dot{\gamma}\boldsymbol{N}ε˙p=γ˙​∂σ∂Φ​=γ˙​N

N\boldsymbol{N}N is called plastic flow vector, γ˙\dot \gammaγ˙​ is the plastic multiplier.

Infinitesimal Isotropic elasticity tensor (fourth-order tensor)

De=2GIS+A(K−23G)I⊗I\mathbf{D}^e=2G\boldsymbol{\rm{I}}_S+A(K-\frac{2}{3}G)\boldsymbol{I}\otimes\boldsymbol{I}De=2GIS​+A(K−32​G)I⊗I

where GGG and KKK are shear and bulk moduli respectively, I\boldsymbol{I}I is the second-order identity and IS\boldsymbol{\rm{I}}_SIS​ is the fourth-order symmetric identity tensor.
4th-order identity tensor I\boldsymbol{\rm I}I: Iijkl=δikδjl\boldsymbol{\rm I}_{ijkl}=\delta_{ik}\delta_{jl}Iijkl​=δik​δjl​
4th-order symmetric identity tensor IS\boldsymbol{\rm{I}}_SIS​: Iijkl=12(δikδjl+δilδjk)\boldsymbol{\rm{I}}_{ijkl}=\frac{1}{2}(\delta_{ik}\delta_{jl}+\delta_{il}\delta_{jk})Iijkl​=21​(δik​δjl​+δil​δjk​)
In plane strain, axisymmetric and 3D analysises:A=1\quad A = 1A=1
In plane stress:A=2GK+43G\quad A = \frac{2G}{K+\frac{4}{3}G}A=K+34​G2G​

DDSDDE

DDSDDE in Abaqus:
D=∂Δσ∂Δε\mathbf{D}=\frac{\partial \Delta\boldsymbol{\sigma}}{\partial \Delta\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}D=∂Δε∂Δσ​

In other books this is expressed as:
Consistant tangent modulus(change within each NR iteration!!):
D=∂σn+1∂εn+1\mathbf{D}=\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{\sigma}_{n+1}}{\partial\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{n+1}}D=∂εn+1​∂σn+1​​

Continuum tangent modulus(Also change within each NR iteration):
notknownyetnot known yetnotknownyet

Continuum tangent operator has nothing to do with Δγ\Delta\gammaΔγ thus is not suitable for return mapping method considering convergence rate.
Anyway, consistent tangent operator rather than continuum is recommended.

UMAT is to give out stress tensor(SUVM), consistent tangent operator (DDSDDE in abaqus)(CTVM) and updated state variables given current state variables, stress tensor, strain tensor and trial strain increment.

Full Newton-Raphson Scheme for FEM

In this scheme, KTK_TKT​ is updated in each iteration during the increment.
A variant of this is the modified NR scheme where KTK_TKT​ remains unchanged during each increment with the initial value.
In my previous multiscale framework, the strain increment δu\delta \mathbf uδu is checked as the threshold, while in this scheme, the residual r\mathbf{r}r is checked. This results in the difference that in this scheme the consistent tangent operator (k) is calculated based on the state of the previous iteration (k-1). In essence they are the same.

State Update for Von Mises Model (Fortran program SUVM)

Given state variables and trial strain, give out updated state variables and stress.
Input:

  • ntype:\rm{ntype}:ntype: analysis type (2→\to→plane strain;3→\to→axisymmetric;others→\to→ not covered for SUVM)
  • iprops:\rm{iprops}:iprops: array of integer materials properties (the only one used in SUVM is nhard: number of sampling points for the piecewise hardening curve)
  • rprops:\rm{rprops}:rprops: array of real material properties. For SUVM, the needs are [E,ν,εˉ0p,σy0,εˉ1p,σy1,⋯ ,εˉnhardp,σy nhard][E,\nu,\bar\varepsilon^p_0,\sigma_{y0},\bar\varepsilon^p_1,\sigma_{y1},\cdots,\bar\varepsilon^p_{\rm{nhard}},\sigma_{y\,{\rm{nhard}}}][E,ν,εˉ0p​,σy0​,εˉ1p​,σy1​,⋯,εˉnhardp​,σynhard​]
  • rstava:\rm{rstava}:rstava: array of state variables other than stress components [εe∗4,εˉp∗1][\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^e*4, \bar\varepsilon^p*1][εe∗4,εˉp∗1], 4 elements for elastic strain, 1 for equivalent plastic strain. For SUVM input, only εˉp\bar\varepsilon^pεˉp of the previous iteration is required.
  • strat:\rm{strat}:strat: εn+1e trial\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{n+1}^{e\,\rm{trial}}εn+1etrial​, array of the elastic trial strains in engineering form. [ε11,ε22,2ε12,ε33][\varepsilon_{11}, \varepsilon_{22}, 2\varepsilon_{12}, \varepsilon_{33}][ε11​,ε22​,2ε12​,ε33​]

Return:

  • Δγ:\Delta\gamma:Δγ: plastic multiplier from return mapping (0 if purely elastic)
  • lalgva: array of logical algorithmic flags or variables. (For SUVM, this contains [ifplas(whether plastic corrector involved), sufail(True: the NR iteration of return mapping fails to converge and the state variables are not updated)])
  • stres:\rm{stres}:stres: array of updated stress components [σ11,σ22,σ12,σ33][\sigma_{11},\sigma_{22},\sigma_{12},\sigma_{33}][σ11​,σ22​,σ12​,σ33​]
  • rstava:\rm{rstava}:rstava: array of state variables other than stress components [εe∗4,εˉp∗1][\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^e*4, \bar\varepsilon^p*1][εe∗4,εˉp∗1], 4 elements for elastic strain, 1 for equivalent plastic strain. For SUVM output, all these elements are updated.

  1. Check type
    If ntype ≠\neq​= 2 (plane strain) and ntype ≠\neq​= 3 (axisymmetric), return error.

  2. Assign and assemble basic parameters
    Δγ=0G=E2(1+ν)K=E3(1−2ν)\Delta \gamma=0 \quad G = \frac{E}{2(1+\nu)} \quad K = \frac{E}{3(1-2\nu)}Δγ=0G=2(1+ν)E​K=3(1−2ν)E​

  3. Elastic predictor

Plane Stress Plasticity

Why plane stress is special?

The generic algorithmic formulas for 3-dimensional cases are based on the fact that stress is unknown and is updated based on strain.
Plane strain/axisymmetric conditions can be seem as degeneration of 3D cases where some components of strain are prescribed and the stress are updated in the same way based on input strain.
While for plane stress problems, stress components rather than strain are prescribed. Thus the normal strain => stress flow cannot be obtained and the 3D numerical integration algorithms should be modified.

    Matrix form is the exact general form for deriving formulas while array form is simply an approach of storing data whose formulas should be derived specifically. The formulas for matrix form can not automatically apply to array form in most cases!!

Three methods

Plane stress constraint at the Gauss point level
Plane stress constraint at the structural level
Plane stress-projected plasticity models

This method only applies to sufficiently simple models which allow closed-form relationship between in-plane and out-of-plane variables to be derived from the plane stress constraint (such as the linear elastic model),
σ13=σ23=σ33=0\quad\sigma_{13}=\sigma_{23}=\sigma_{33}=0σ13​=σ23​=σ33​=0

For other complex models, the other two methods are recommended.

Plane stress-projected Von Mises model

The general 3D von Mises model with isotropic strain hardening:
ε˙=ε˙e+ε˙pσ=De:εeΦ=3J2(s)−σy(εˉp)ε˙=γ˙∂Φ∂σ=γ˙32s∥s∥εˉ˙p=γ˙γ˙≥0,Φ≤0,γ˙Φ=0.\begin{aligned} &\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}=\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}^e+\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}^p\\ &\boldsymbol{\sigma}=\boldsymbol{D}^e:\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^e\\ &\Phi = \sqrt{3J_2(\boldsymbol{s})}-\sigma_y(\bar{\varepsilon}^p)\\ &\dot{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}=\dot{\gamma}\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{\Phi}}{\partial\boldsymbol{\sigma}}=\dot{\gamma}\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}\frac{\boldsymbol{s}}{\|\boldsymbol{s}\|}\\ &\dot{\bar{\varepsilon}}^p=\dot{\gamma}\\ &\dot{\gamma}\ge0,\quad\Phi\leq0,\quad\dot{\gamma}\Phi=0. \end{aligned}​ε˙=ε˙e+ε˙pσ=De:εeΦ=3J2​(s)​−σy​(εˉp)ε˙=γ˙​∂σ∂Φ​=γ˙​23​​∥s∥s​εˉ˙p=γ˙​γ˙​≥0,Φ≤0,γ˙​Φ=0.​

Orthogonal matrix AAA（正交矩阵）:
AAT=EAA^T=EAAT=E
The column/row vectors of AAA are orthogonal to each other and are all unit vectors. And we have AT=A−1A^T=A^{-1}AT=A−1.
This matrix can be obtained from the eigenvectors as basis.

SUVMPS(State update procedur for the von Mises model in plane stress)

Pure input:

  • ntype:\rm{ntype}:ntype: analysis type (1→\to→plane stress;2→\to→plane strain;3→\to→axisymmetric)

  • iprops:\rm{iprops}:iprops: array of integer materials properties (the only one used in SUVM is nhard: number of sampling points for the piecewise hardening curve)

  • rprops:\rm{rprops}:rprops: array of real material properties. For SUVMPS, the needs are [E,ν,εˉ0p,σy0,εˉ1p,σy1,⋯ ,εˉnhardp,σy nhard][E,\nu,\bar\varepsilon^p_0,\sigma_{y0},\bar\varepsilon^p_1,\sigma_{y1},\cdots,\bar\varepsilon^p_{\rm{nhard}},\sigma_{y\,{\rm{nhard}}}][E,ν,εˉ0p​,σy0​,εˉ1p​,σy1​,⋯,εˉnhardp​,σynhard​]

  • strat:\rm{strat}:strat: εn+1e trial\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{n+1}^{e\,\rm{trial}}εn+1etrial​, array of the elastic trial strains in engineering form. [ε11,ε22,2ε12,ε33][\varepsilon_{11}, \varepsilon_{22}, 2\varepsilon_{12}, \varepsilon_{33}][ε11​,ε22​,2ε12​,ε33​]

Input and updated:

  • rstava:\rm{rstava}:rstava: array of state variables other than stress components [ε11e,ε22e,2ε12e,ε33e,εˉp][\varepsilon_{11}^e,\varepsilon_{22}^e,2\varepsilon_{12}^e,\varepsilon_{33}^e,\bar\varepsilon^p][ε11e​,ε22e​,2ε12e​,ε33e​,εˉp], 4 elements for elastic strain in engineering form, 1 for equivalent plastic strain. For SUVMPS input, only εˉp\bar\varepsilon^pεˉp of the previous iteration is required. These elements should be updated through this program.

Pure output:

  • Δγ:\Delta\gamma:Δγ: plastic multiplier from return mapping (0 if purely elastic)
  • lalgva: array of logical algorithmic flags or variables. (For SUVMPS, this contains [ifplas(whether plastic corrector involved), sufail(True: the NR iteration of return mapping fails to converge and the state variables are not updated)])
  • stres:\rm{stres}:stres: array of updated stress components [σ11,σ22,σ12][\sigma_{11},\sigma_{22},\sigma_{12}][σ11​,σ22​,σ12​]

  7. Return other parameters

Elastoplastic consistent tangent operator

CTVMPS(Consistent tangent operator for the von Mises model in plane stress)

Pure input:

  • Δγ:\Delta\gamma:Δγ: plastic multiplier from SUVMPS (0 for purely elastic)
  • stres:\rm{stres}:stres: array of updated stress tensor σn+1=[σ11,σ22,σ12]\boldsymbol{\sigma}_{n+1}=[\sigma_{11},\sigma_{22},\sigma_{12}]σn+1​=[σ11​,σ22​,σ12​] from SUVMPS
  • rstava:\rm{rstava}:rstava: array of updated state parameters [ε11e,ε22e,2ε12e,ε33e,εˉp][\varepsilon_{11}^e,\varepsilon_{22}^e,2\varepsilon_{12}^e,\varepsilon_{33}^e,\bar\varepsilon^p][ε11e​,ε22e​,2ε12e​,ε33e​,εˉp] (4+1) from SUVMPS. Only εˉn+1p\bar\varepsilon^p_{n+1}εˉn+1p​ is used in CTVMPS.

  • rprops:\rm{rprops}:rprops: array of real material parameters (EEE,ν\nuν,εˉ0p,σy0,εˉ1p,σy1...\bar\varepsilon^p_0,\sigma_{y0},\bar\varepsilon^p_1,\sigma_{y1}...εˉ0p​,σy0​,εˉ1p​,σy1​...)

  • ntype:\rm{ntype}:ntype: analysis type (plane stress(1); plane strain(2); axisymmetric(3))

Abaqus Subroutine

User subroutine interface

SUBROUTINE UMAT(STRESS,STATEV,DDSDDE,SSE,SPD,SCD,
     1 RPL,DDSDDT,DRPLDE,DRPLDT,
     2 STRAN,DSTRAN,TIME,DTIME,TEMP,DTEMP,PREDEF,DPRED,CMNAME,
     3 NDI,NSHR,NTENS,NSTATV,PROPS,NPROPS,COORDS,DROT,PNEWDT,
     4 CELENT,DFGRD0,DFGRD1,NOEL,NPT,LAYER,KSPT,JSTEP,KINC)
C
      INCLUDE 'ABA_PARAM.INC'
C
      CHARACTER*80 CMNAME
      DIMENSION STRESS(NTENS),STATEV(NSTATV),
     1 DDSDDE(NTENS,NTENS),DDSDDT(NTENS),DRPLDE(NTENS),
     2 STRAN(NTENS),DSTRAN(NTENS),TIME(2),PREDEF(1),DPRED(1),
     3 PROPS(NPROPS),COORDS(3),DROT(3,3),DFGRD0(3,3),DFGRD1(3,3),
     4 JSTEP(4)

Variables to be defined (Inputs and outputs)

In all situations

  • DDSDDE(NTENS,NTENS)
    Jacobian matrix of the constitutive model to be calculated by UMAT.
    D=∂Δσ∂Δε\mathbf{D}=\frac{\partial\Delta\boldsymbol{\sigma}}{\partial\Delta\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}D=∂Δε∂Δσ​

    Output.

  • STRESS(NTENS)
    Array of the stress tensor.
    Passed in and updated.

  • STATEV(NSTAVA)
    Array containing the solution-dependent state variables.
    The size of it is specified in *DEPVAR in Abaqus.
    Passed in and updated.

  • SSE, SPD, SCD
    Specific elastic strain energy(SSE), specific plastic dissipation(SPD), specific creep dissipation(SCD).
    Passed in and updated.

Only in a fully coupled thermal-stress or a coupled thermal-electrical-structural analysis

  • RPL
    Volumetric heat generation per unit time at the end of the increment caused by mechanical working of the material.
    Output
  • DDSDDT(NTENS)
    Variation of the stress increments with respect to temperature
    Output
  • DRPLDE(NTENS)
    Variation of RPL with respect to strain increments.
    Output
  • DRPLDT
    Variation of RPL with respect to temperature
    Output

Only in a geostatic stress procedure or a coupled pore fluid diffusion/stress analysis for pore pressure cohesive elements

  • RPL
    RPL is used to indicate whether or not a cohesive element is open to the tangential flow of pore fluid. Set RPL equal to 0 if there is no tangential flow; otherwise, assign a nonzero value to RPL if an element is open. Once opened, a cohesive element will remain open to the fluid flow.

Variables that can be updated

  • PNEWDT
    Ratio of suggested new time increment to the time increment being used.

Variables passed in for information

All the variables are passed in if not specifically pointed out.

  • STRAN(NTENS)
    Array of total strains at the beginning of the increment.
    For cases with thermal expansion, this strain is the one with thermal strains subtracted.
  • DSTRAN(NTENS)
    Array of strain increments.
    For cases with thermal expansion, this is the one with thermal strain increment subtracted.
  • TIME(1)
    Value of time step at the beginning of the current increment.
  • TIME(2)
    Value of total time at the beginning of the current increment.
  • DTIME
    Time increment.
  • TEMP
    Temperature at the start of the increment.
  • DTEMP
    Increment of temperature.
  • PREDEF
    Array of interpolated values of predefined field variables based on values read at the nodes at this point at the start of this increment.
  • DPRED
    Array of increments of predefined field variables.
  • CMNAME
    User-defined material name. Do not start with "ABQ_".
  • NDI
    Number of direct stress components at this point.
  • NSHR
    Number of engineering shear stress components at this point.
  • NTENS
    Size of the stress or strain component array(NDI + NSHR).
  • NSTATV
    Number of solution-dependent state variables associated with this material.(*DEPVAR)
  • NPROPS
    Number of material constants associated with this user material.
  • PROPS(NPROPS)
    Array of material constants associated with this user material.(Defined in material constants in Abaqus/CAE)
  • COORDS
    Array of the coordinates of this point. (For cases with geometric nonlinearity, it contains the current coordinates otherwise the original ones.)
  • DROT(3,3)
    Rotation increment matrix.
    This matrix represents the increment of rigid body rotation of the basis system in which the components of stress (STRESS) and strain (STRAN) are stored. It is provided so that vector- or tensor-valued state variables can be rotated appropriately in this subroutine: stress and strain components are already rotated by this amount before UMAT is called. This matrix is passed in as a unit matrix for small-displacement analysis and for large-displacement analysis if the basis system for the material point rotates with the material (as in a shell element or when a local orientation is used).
  • CELENT
    Characteristic element length.
    This is the typical length of a line across an element for a first-order element; it is half of the same typical length for a second-order element. For beams and trusses it is a characteristic length along the element axis. For membranes and shells it is a characteristic length in the reference surface. For axisymmetric elements it is a characteristic length in the plane only. For cohesive elements it is equal to the constitutive thickness.
  • DFGRD0(3,3)
    Array containing the deformation gradient at the beginning of the increment.
    If a local orientation is defined at the material point, the deformation gradient components are expressed in the local coordinate system defined by the orientation at the beginning of the increment.
  • DFGRD1(3,3)
    Array containing the deformation gradient at the end of the increment.
    If a local orientation is defined at the material point, the deformation gradient components are expressed in the local coordinate system defined by the orientation. This array is set to the identity matrix if nonlinear geometric effects are not included in the step definition associated with this increment.
    Output
  • NOEL
    Element number.
  • NPT
    Integration point number.
  • LAYER
    Layer number.(for composite shells and layered solids.)
  • KSPT
    Section point number within the current layer.
  • JSTEP(1)
    Step number.
  • JSTEP(2)
    Procedure type key.
  • JSTEP(3)
    Flag of geometric nonlinearity.
    If NLGEOM = YES: =1, else: =0
  • KINC
    Increment number.
